40|$|The paper investigates in {{a dynamic}} context {{the effect of}} Chief Executive Officer (CEO) <b>bonus</b> and salary <b>payments</b> on banks’ {{technical}} efficiency levels. Our methodological framework incorporates the latest developments on the probabilistic approach of efficiency measurement as introduced by Bădin et al. (2012). We apply time-dependent conditional efficiency estimates to analyse a sample of 37 US banks for the period from 2003 to 2012. The empirical evidence reveals a non-linear relationship between CEO <b>bonus</b> and salary <b>payments</b> and banks’ efficiency levels. More specifically it is reported that salary and <b>bonus</b> <b>payments</b> affect differently banks’ technological change and technological catch-up levels. Finally, the empirical evidence suggests that higher salary and <b>bonus</b> <b>payments</b> are not always aligned with higher technical efficiency levels...|$|R
